<br>
Given a few weeks to mull it over, I've changed my mind <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I think they used their position to essentially write new law into effect, not interpret existing law.<br>
<br>
While I wholly agree with the conclusions they came to (that government has no business whatsoever regulating what people do in their bedrooms or how they do it), I have to concede that their decision isn't based on an interpretation of existing constitutional law.  Just because I think something <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>should</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> be constitutionally protected doesn't change the fact that it <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>isn't</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, and it's not the Supreme Court's job to put it in there.<br>
<br>
They pretty much come right out and say it, when they talk about changing attitudes of the public, blah blah blah, etc.  If public attitudes had changed that much the public would have modified the constitution itself (either protecting such behaviour on the national level, or prohibiting those kinds of laws on the local level).  Involving themselves in the politics of the case sets a bad precedent too, because it just invites more of the same not only on their level but at levels below them. <br>
<br>
So anyways, I'm changing my mind.  I thought that qualified as news, so there ya go.<br>
<br>
- Syll<br>
<br>
PS: What prompted the change was a little bit the discussion that went on in that thread, but also all the talk of late about the psychotically Right-wing judges Bush is trying to appoint to the court... which got me thinking about how bad it is that people are trying to short-cut the democratic process by letting a panel of 9 essentially create law through skewed &quot;interpretations&quot; of existing ones... which got me thinking about that case again. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=twotribes>Twotribes</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Board Troll</span><br>  Posts: 1019<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/25/03 10:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=689.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I changed my mind...</span><hr size=1> Funny, every Judge nominated by Bush has the endorsement of the very body's of judges and lawyers that the Democrats claimed were essential. How exactly are they right wing nutjobs? <br>
